\details{
\strong{Data Triage and Matrix Smoothing}

Genomic SEM relies on asymptotic covariance matrices (\eqn{V}) generated by LDSC. These matrices are frequently non-positive definite due to sampling variation or minor missingness across GWAS cohorts. \code{umxGSEM} implements an automatic triage system:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{Level 1 (Clean)}: Matrices are strictly positive definite and pass directly to the optimizer.
\item \strong{Level 2 (Smoothed)}: Negative eigenvalues are detected. The matrices are smoothed using \code{Matrix::nearPD} to restore positive definiteness before estimation.
}

\emph{Fiduciary Warning}: Models estimated using smoothed matrices are tagged with a \code{gsem_triage} attribute. Downstream functions like \code{umxCompare} will read this attribute and warn the user that Satorra-Bentler difference tests may report artificial precision.

\strong{Engine Integration}
\code{umxGSEM} automatically configures the C++ backend to cache the implied Jacobian matrix. This is a structural requirement for computing Satorra-Bentler (2010) scaled difference tests in \code{umxCompare}.

\strong{OpenMx WLS data (modern only)}

Genomic SEM needs precomputed summary matrices \(S\) (genetic cov) and \(V\) (sampling cov of
\(\mathrm{vech}(S)\)). OpenMx WLS consumes these via the \strong{modern} \code{mxData} interface only:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{mxData(numObs = 1,
       observedStats = list(cov = S, useWeight = W, asymCov = V))
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

with \code{W = diag(1/diag(V))} for DWLS. \code{umxGSEM} also reorders \code{V} into OpenMx residual order
(all variances, then free covariances) and sets dimnames \verb{var_*} / \verb{poly_*_*}.

\strong{umx hard-refuses} OpenMx \code{type = "acov"} / \code{MxDataLegacyWLS} data (historical name trap:
\code{acov} meant useWeight; \code{fullWeight} meant asymCov). Do not construct that form; use
\code{observedStats} as above or raw data + \code{type = "DWLS"}.
}
